They are not 100 metres away from each other: on Tuesday the new B 33 pedestrian temple at the village parking lot was put into operation in Gutach - in sight of the older town hall light.
Two plants so close together: intention or a sign-bourgeois prank?
This question was clearly answered yesterday by Guinach's mayor.
"The city hall light was installed at the time, because it secured the school path," explained Eckert yesterday.
The traffic lights secure both cyclists and bus passengers and the mountain inhabitants.
The plant, which was officially operational yesterday, was important for the Sulzbachweg / Kirchstraße crossing area.
We have the museum, two churches, spa park, bus stop, a doctor and a bank as well as the traffic flow from the residential area "Grub."
"With the high traffic and pedestrian traffic, a further light had to come in for their safety," said Eckert.
This is also confirmed by Peter Arnold of the State Council of Offenburg.
"According to current measurements on the B 33, about 12 000 vehicles pass through the municipality of Gutach every day, of which about 10% are heavy-duty traffic," says Arnold.
Therefore, the construction of another light is more than necessary: "Safety is just going on here," says Arnold.
A total of four traffic shows were held, a roundabout was also planned, but because of the narrow area in the Sulzbachweg / Kirchstraße area was rejected.
According to Arnold, everything was tested before in the location of the traffic lights: "By means of an extra transport loaded for us with particularly long logs of wood we have tested whether these vehicles can go out from the Sulzbachweg to the B 33 without changing the traffic lights."
The traffic light system itself, which costs about 15 000 euros, is "the most modern thing that is currently available on the market," explained Arnold.
The system is equipped with colored LEDs that are so strong that the lights can be seen by the drivers, for example, even in the low sun.
And it is also economical: the older light systems use about 100 watts, the new just eight watts.
There are three light systems per direction of travel.
Arnold explained the technology of the new system: it is equipped with two radar sensors.
When the pedestrian pushes the traffic button, the upper radar sensor tests the traffic situation.
If the road is free, it will come directly green for the pedestrian, if not, it will take about 15 seconds.
Another radar sensor checks whether the green phase for the pedestrian can be completed.
"If a group or disabled people go across the street, the green phase will be extended, so everyone will come safely across the road," Arnold said.
Of course, the driver had to think as a partner here and watch the road.
This was not the case yesterday: The light for pedestrians was only a little bit green, a top-class vehicle was rushing through - with a light red.
