A black box in the car?
US road planners are looking for a source of money to repair the falling highway system, and believe to have found the solution in a small black box that can be found in the dashboard of each car.
The devices that record every mile of the road and report the information to the authorities are at the heart of a controversial attempt by Washington and the state planning offices to revise the outdated system of financing US roads.
The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly opened up an intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertaires have allied with environmental groups and are in favour of the government being able to use the small boxes for the recording of the hit kilometres - and possibly where they were driven - and then use the information for the calculation of tax deductions.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and has a number of data protection concerns.
But while in Congress one cannot agree on a procedure, several states no longer wait.
They are currently examining how they can switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile.
Thousands of car drivers have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS monitoring.
This is really a must for our country.
"It is nothing we may only use," said Hasan Ikhrata, Managing Director of Southern California Assn. of Governments, who plans to record the miles that have been driven by all the Californian car drivers in the state from 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is financed from taxes, is broke by the US-Americans paying at the pump column.
But in America, it's not as much gas as it used to be.
Cars use less fuel.
The state oil tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 euro cents per litre) has not increased for 20 years.
With high fuel prices, politicians do not dare to raise the tax by a cent.
"The fuel tax is simply not sustainable," said Lee Munnich, an expert on traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
"This is the most useful alternative in the long term," he said.
bureaucrats call it a mile-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is popular with urban liberals, for example, because the tax could be used to influence driving behaviour in such a way that congestion and climate-harmful exhaust gases are reduced.
The California planners rely on the system to develop strategies to achieve the ambitious, legally-based targets of the state on climate change.
But the Republican Bill Shuster from Pennsylvania, Chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also pleased with the idea of making drivers pay after a distance.
"This is not a tax that disappears in a black hole," says Adrian Moore, Vice President for Guidelines at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also supported by two former US transport ministers, who in a report in 2011 called on Congress to move towards mile-based settlement.
The U.S. Senate approved a $90 million-worth pilot project last year, which would have included 10,000 cars.
But the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the advance and thus responded to the concerns of Members from rural areas who represent people who often have to travel many miles on their way to work or to the city in everyday life.
However, several states and large cities are moving on their own.
The most committed is Oregon, which currently acquires 5,000 drivers for the country's largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the miles instead of the oil tax to the state.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering this.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transport ministries of 17 states on the east coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently examining how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where 50 volunteers were recently equipped with the equipment, drivers were sceptical about the idea that the government could follow any of its movements.
"Concerns about Big Brother and such things were a big problem," explains Alauddin Khan, Head of Strategy and Result Management at the Nevada Ministry of Transport.
People didn't want it.
When the test started, the ACLU of Nevada warned on its website: "It would be relatively easy to turn the tachograph into adult surveillance devices."
There was no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to collect data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is one of a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that the state can use to capture the kilometres that have been driven, but not exactly when and where.
That, according to Khan, would also make the public more well-founded.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small start-up company called True Mileage in California.
The company was originally not involved in helping state states to tax drivers.
Rather, it was their aim to take a stand in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers are to pay on the basis of the miles that have been driven.
But the devices tested by her are also interesting for the road planners, because they do not work with GPS and provide only limited information, which is regularly uploaded by modem.
"People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded," said Ryan Morrison, Managing Director of True Mileage.
Some of these public pilot programmes have made major mistakes.
There are much cheaper and less intrusive ways of implementing this.
In Oregon, the planners experiment to give drivers a number of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they do not choose any device at all and instead pay a flat-rate fee on the basis of the average miles travelled by all the residents of the state.
Other bodies hope to be able to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more functions than with less.
In New York City, traffic officials want to develop a tax-based device that can also pay parking fees, have to pay insurance for only a few miles and to collect speed data from other vehicles in real time, thanks to which drivers can avoid congestion.
"Drivers would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system," it says in a planning document of the city.
Some traffic planners, however, wonder whether the whole talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said that Congress could simply solve the problem of the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund by increasing the fuel tax.
An additional one-off fee or an annual charge could be imposed on drivers using hybrid vehicles or other vehicles using little petrol, so that they also pay a fair share.
"There is no reason for an operation if an aspirin is sufficient," explains Randy Rentschler, the Commission's head of legislation and public affairs.
If we do, hundreds of millions of car drivers will worry about their privacy and many other things.
