US border: "Super Tunnel" discovered for drug smuggling
On the border between Mexico and the United States, investigators have discovered and shut down a "super tunnel" for drug smuggling.
As the US customs reported, the more than 500-metre-long tube between Tijuana and San Diego was equipped with electricity, railway tracks and a ventilation system.
Three suspects were arrested, eight tons of marijuana and almost 150 kilograms of cocaine.
According to the information, the tunnel had not yet been used.
"These cartels are stupid if they think they can dig out under the radar," said the U.S. Southern California General Attorney, Laura Duffy, at a press conference in front of a warehouse in San Diego, where the one end of the tunnel was discovered.
Duffy said to the drug gangs: "If you continue to build such tunnels and try to use them, we are determined to make this a huge waste of your dirty money."
Both the US authorities and the Mexican security forces are in a long-term fight against the drug cartels.
Since 2006, more than 77.000 people have been killed in the context of drug crime in Mexico.
Designed by experts
Because of the complex equipment of the tunnel, the investigators assume that it was designed by architects and engineers and that the construction took about a year.
The track system was equipped so that electric vehicles could be used there.
On the Mexican side is the access in a building that is 80 metres from the border.
According to the authorities, a ladder leads 20 meters into the depth to the actual tunnel entrance.
The tunnel has a cross-section of 1.20 meters high and 90 centimeters wide.
It would also have been suitable to promote illegal immigration in the direction of the USA.
Two of the suspects were arrested in connection with the cocaine finding.
The third, a Mexican, was caught for the confiscated marijuana.
All three are under threat of life-long deprivation, as officials said.
Since 2006, eight such tunnels have been discovered, and the press conference in San Diego continued.
It was the first time that cocaine was found in such a tunnel construction.
Usually cocaine is smuggled in smaller quantities and not through tunnels.
This is shown by the "despair" of the drug gangs, whose traditional routes have now been cut off, said Bill Sherman of the DEA drug investigation in San Diego.
They would do anything to get to the United States.
