Esa decides on large space emissions: missions for billions
Remote planets, gravitational waves or black holes - experts from the European Space Agency now have to agree on two major projects they want to start in the coming years.
30 proposals were available, five are still in the race.
Far worlds.
More than 1000 planets on other stars have already found astronomers.
No one knows if there are lives on at least some of them.
The selection is difficult: should one look for gravitational waves?
Or rather to explore the origin of the cosmos?
Or search for Earth-like planets and perhaps discover alien life?
The European Space Agency, Esa, is in the process of asking these questions.
For their program "Cosmic Vision," they are looking for ideas for two major space projects, which should make a decisive contribution to research.
The budget for such "L-Missions" is about one billion euros each.
The start is expected to be 2028 and 2034.
In early September, the elite of European space research met in Paris to discuss proposals for such missions.
There were 30 ideas to be discussed, five of which have now come to a closer choice.
A large number of bodies examined the proposals and followed up with the researchers.
In the next few days, a final decision will be taken by the scientific programme committee.
A total of four major questions have been selected by the Esa, to which the missions of the "Cosmic Vision" programme, launched in 2007, will find answers.
What are the conditions for the development of planets and life?
The exact processes of the creation of stars from large gas clouds - and thus also of planets that surround these stars - are still in the proverbial dark.
A large infrared telescope in space could penetrate this dark.
And if a star has planets, under what circumstances can life be created there?
In order to look into this question, the "Cheops" space telescope will start in 2017, which will further examine 500 well-known planetary systems in our near environment.
The possibilities are limited, however, Cheops is a small mission with a budget of 150 million euros.
With larger instruments, the astronomers could depict Earth-like planets and even analyse the composition of their atmospheres and thus look for "biomarkers": gases that are considered to be an indication of biological activity.
How does the solar system work?
This question, too, is to finally give an indication of the conditions for the creation of life.
The magnetic activity of a star and the interaction of its magnetic field and the particle radiation from it with the planetary system play an important role.
In our solar system, these processes can be examined in an exemplary way.
With the "Solar Orbiter" the Esa has already approved a M-Class mission (where the budget is about half a billion euros) for this question.
The probe is to start in 2017 and closely monitor the surface and activity of the sun.
The researchers are also very interested in Jupiter and its moons.
They want to find out what role the giant planet played in the development of the solar system.
The Esa is the first of the three L-missions of the "Cosmic Vision" program.
The "Juice" (Jupiter Icy Moons Explorer) probe is expected to begin its journey in 2022.
Eight years later, it reaches Jupiter and is intended to study the atmosphere of the planet, as well as the icy moons of Europe, Kallisto and Ganymed.
What are the basic physical laws of the universe?
Space offers many possibilities to study matter under extreme conditions and to examine whether the laws of nature we know are still valid there.
Perhaps there are also differences that could show the physicists the way to a new theory under which all known natural laws can be united.
How did the universe come into being and what does it consist of?
13.7 billion years ago, our cosmos was created by the Big Bang.
In addition to the common matter of stars, planets and living beings like us, there are dark matter, the gravity of which is holding together galaxies and galaxy clusters, and dark energy, by whose action the expansion of the universe is accelerating.
So far, the researchers do not know which physical laws were valid in the first few seconds of the Big Bang, nor what Dark Matter and Dark Energy consist of.
With "Euclid," the Esa has already approved an M-mission, the launch of which is planned for 2020.
With a special telescope, the probe is to examine the distribution of matter in the universe for the first time in the entire sky, thus enabling conclusions to be drawn on the nature of dark matter and dark energy.
Who could make the race
Of the 30 proposals, only two will be left at the end of the selection process.
According to many experts, "E-Lisa," has the best chances of obtaining an L-mission, a demanding concept for the detection of gravitational waves.
Among these, physicists understand changes in the structure of space time that Albert Einstein had predicted almost 100 years ago.
They have not been shown to this day.
Elisa could do this, hope the scientists behind the project.
The mission provides for a detector consisting of two or three probes, which is stationed in space.
In contrast to installations on Earth, it could also prove gravitational waves that were created in the Big Bang, and thus provide new insights about the development of the cosmos.
Four other proposals are still competing for the second L-mission: a large X-ray telescope called "Athena," which is to explore black holes, "Icy Planets," another mission to the outer planets of the solar system, "Prism," a mission to measure the cosmic background radiation, and the "Exoplanet Finder," which is to track and investigate Earth-like planets.
There have already been proposals for the return of samples from Mars, for the exploration of the moon, Venus and asteroids, and for solar physics.
