Pawns booming in Singapore, as the crisis has arrived in the middle class
In a pawnshop in the Bendemeer shopping centre in Singapore, Janani Amirthalinga exchanges a golden bracelet, a ring and a pair of earrings to pay the school fees of her daughters.
"My husband and I have just bought a house, and all my money is in it," says Amirthalinga.
Although every month she deserves 3,000 Singapore dollars (about 1,730 euros) as an administrative employee and her husband also works, the monthly family income is not enough, she explains.
In fact, demand in parts of South-East Asia - where household debt is increasing - is so high that ValueMax, where it has made its exchange, has become the third pawnhouse listed on the Sinapurian stock exchange this week.
The pairing of jewelry is not only a fast way to get money - 1,300 Singapore dollars in the case of Janani Amirthalinga - but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawns in Singapore require an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, which is just above the 15.4 percent that the United Overseas Bank requires, a local lender with a branch in the same shopping mall.
Pawns, however, offer the advantage that there is no need for a review of the creditworthiness or income evidence, which is why loans are faster than banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region turn to pawns, after families feel the pressure of rising living costs and increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a looser fiscal policy in the developed economic areas, families with lower and medium income are looking for pawns to compensate for the difference in the stuttering economy.
This week, the rating agency called Standard & Poor's growing budgetary debt, mainly through rising mortgages, a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
According to the Agency, Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest budgetary debt in Asia in relation to gross domestic product.
Malaysia is at the top of the list with 80% of GDP, an increase of 60% still in 2008.
Economists are also worried about the high consumer debt in Thailand, which has just come out of a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, the data showed a continuing deterioration in exports and a decline in consumer demand.
"In the end, this means that in view of increasing costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible," says Song Seng Wun, economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
In the past two years, the historical high levels of gold prices have increased the trend towards the pairing of personal objects, as people take the opportunity to turn the family's jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged objects are gold in the 200 pawns of the city state.
People say to themselves, "The gold price looks good, let's pawn Grand Mother's gold chain and bring it back next month."
The largest Thai Pfandhaus operator, EasyMoney, has experienced a 20% increase in its branches in recent months.
The growth in the pawn business is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only into neighbouring Malaysia - where the company operates four houses - but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, CEO of ValueMax.
The company is financing this with 60 percent of the 66 million Singapore dollars that it took this week with the IPO in Singapore.
While some lenders were in the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah explained that pawns would not only be more favourable than other lenders, but also not directly increased the debt.
"Customers do not borrow items they already own, and the liquid of personal valuables does not increase household debt," she explains.
The pawn-lending business is increasingly accepted as short-term, secured financing.
And not all people who use pawnshop are in financial difficulties.
Rich people from Singapore also come to the stores of ValueMax to pledge gold bars and Rolex watches, for which they receive up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
We have customers from every social shift.
"These include wealthy people who lend something for a business or investment in the short term, or small companies that have to bridge bottlenecks in the cash flow," says Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money very quickly.
