Syria has destroyed its ability to produce chemical weapons, so a monitoring group
Syria had destroyed important facilities for the production of chemical weapons and grid gas munitions, said the global chemical weapons surveillance group on Thursday, while in the north of the country there were serious clashes near one of the sites where the suspected toxic substances are stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group announced that more than 120,000 people had been killed three years ago since the beginning of the civil war.
The announcement of the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons (OPCW) came one day before the date on
1 November, which the Damascus-based organization established in The Hague had set up to destroy all facilities for the production of chemical weapons or to make "inoperable," including all machines for mixing chemicals into toxic gas and filling ammunition.
The completion of this process, which is basically the first stage of destruction, is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable aimed at the destruction of all the chemical weapons of Syria by mid-2014.
The destruction of the facilities means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
However, Damascus must still begin to destroy the existing weapons and supplies.
According to assumptions, there are about 1,000 tonnes of chemicals and weapons in the country, including mustard gas and the nerve gas sarin.
The announcement came at a time when fighting took place in the city of Safira on Thursday, from which experts say that there is a chemical weapons production facility and storage facilities, as the UK-based Syrian Human Rights Observatory reported.
The activist group, which is following the number of dead over a network of activists in Syria, said on Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 were civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government side, 29.954 of them belonged to the army of President Bashar Assad, that 18,678 were government-friendly fighters and 187 Lebanese Hezbollah militias.
Also among the dead were 2,202 army soldiers and 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On July 25, the UN estimated the number of dead in this conflict to be 100,000 since March 2011.
This number has not been updated so far.
