Assad's troops have been fighting against the rebels in Safira for weeks, many of whom have connections with al-Qaeda groups.
The Observatory said there were losses on both sides on Thursday, but did not mention any details.
The fighting underscores the danger that the chemical weapons inspectors are exposed to, because their mission to liberate Syria from its toxic arsenal is a race against time in the midst of a raging civil war.
According to the OPCW, which is working closely with the United Nations, the team "is now convinced that it has seen and witnessed all the important production and mixing / filling facilities mentioned by Syria."
Therefore, "no further inspection activities are currently planned."
At the beginning of the week, the inspectors had declared that they had completed the first round of the inspections and visited 21 of the 23 sites specified by Damascus.
The inspectors said it was not possible to visit two bodies because of security concerns.
On Thursday, the OPWC stated that the two sites had been "abandoned and that the objects of the chemical weapons programme there had been moved to other mentioned facilities that were inspected."
It was not immediately clear whether the site in Safira was one of the two facilities that the OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has presented a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which will have to be approved by the OPWC Executive Committee next month.
"I draw my hat to the bravery and courage that you have all shown in fulfilling the most challenging mission ever carried out by this organisation," said Ahmed Uzumcu, the Director-General of the monitoring organisation in a comment published by OPCW.
For three years now, the main Sunni Muslim rebels in this civil war have been fighting against Assad's government and their security forces, to which many members of the Alawites belong, a division of Shiite Islam.
With regard to further developments, the head of the observation group, Rami Abdurrahman, said that there had been a strong explosion in an air defense facility in the Syrian coastal province of Latakia on Wednesday.
The cause of the explosion was unknown, he said.
