FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in aircraft (but do not have mobile calls)
From departure to landing, passengers can now use their electronic devices for reading, working, playing, listening to music and watching films, but not by phone, according to the new guidelines published by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the USA on Thursday.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
The speed with which they would be implemented depends on the airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta explained at a press conference.
The airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the training manuals of the air crew and the rules for the storage of the equipment in accordance with the new rules.
The FAA stated that it had already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic equipment in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the condition of the plan, we could approve the extended use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA announced in a statement.
At present, passengers have to shut down smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They may not start them again until the plane has reached a height of three kilometres and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the landing, passengers must turn it off again and not start it again before the plane has landed.
According to the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are protected against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the equipment even at the start, landing and on the rolling field, said the FAA.
Most new transport aircraft and other aircraft that have been upgraded for the use of Wi-Fi at larger heights should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the professional flight crew, welcomed the changes.
"If the new scheme is safely implemented - and we work closely with the airline in this respect - both sides will benefit," said Glading.
We are, to be honest, tired of having to feel like a guard on this subject.
However, Internet connections to the surfing, exchange of emails, text messages or download of data less than three kilometres were still prohibited, the Authority explained.
Passengers are asked to move smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends," the Scrabble-like online game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011, when he had to leave a jet of American Airlines in public, because he refused to shut down the device while the plane was parked on the platform.
And heavier devices like laptops must continue to be stowed, as there is a risk of injury here if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile calls during the flight are also prohibited.
The regulatory competence for telephone calls lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not with the FAA.
FAA may lift a ban on certain electronic devices at start and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, National Transport Security Experts on CBS News, said mobile phones were still considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem not only because they could cause potential interference with navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that the transmission from the air can also interfere with transmission masts," said Rosenker.
An industry advisory committee set up by the FAA to study this issue recommended last month that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA has increased to ease restrictions on use.
Critics like the democratic senator Claire McCaskill from Missouri believe there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the equipment has become omnipresent.
Some studies mention that up to a third of the passengers forget or ignore the device's shutdown.
The FAA began in 1966 to restrict the use of electronic devices by air passengers after reports of interference of navigation and communication devices by VHF radio carried by passengers had become known, which at that time represented the latest technology.
New aircraft are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also so designed and approved by the FAA that they do not care about electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi for a few years when the flight height is reached.
The flyers adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also more insensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the greater use of electronic equipment under the new guidelines, said Huerta.
Today's electronic devices generally provide much less radio than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only give up minimal radiation when you turn over.
But when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
One of the supporters of easing the restrictions on the use of equipment by passengers is Amazon.com. com.
In 2011, company staff invited a passenger plane full of Kindle E-Reader and made a test flight to identify problems, but could not find any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using devices.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he considered the device to be a real fault, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said that there were only a few reports of pilots in favour of a malfunction of aircraft systems by the devices, and most of them were very old.
The committee, however, recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order the disconnection of the equipment by the passengers in the event of instrument landing under poor visual conditions.
A group from the travel industry welcomed the changes and described them as a reasonable adjustment for travellers who would now be fully equipped with technology.
"We are pleased that the FAA recognises that a pleasant passenger experience is not in conflict with safety," said Roger Dow, CEO of the U.S. Travel Association.
