Hearing before the Royal Commission: Two YMCA employees charged with sexual crimes against Jonathan Lord
Two YMCA staff from New South Wales (NSW) had been charged with sexual offences related to children before the charges against the child-ward Jonathan Lord of Caringbah were raised in 2011, as the Royal Commission for Sexual Abuse of Children learned.
However, in the opening statement to the Commission, the YMCA had stated that "the organisation had never had to do with an incident of sexual abuse of children."
Managing Director Phillip Hare was asked about a case in which a YMCA employee had been charged with child pornography and another in which a sports teacher of the YMCA Caringbah Hall had been convicted in 1991 for the abuse of children entrusted to him.
Hare said, one of the Commission's assistants, that he knew about the first case but did not know the second one.
He admitted that the opening statement of the YMCA to the Commission was also inaccurate in the claim that "there have been external reviews of the YMCA in which the YMCA was recognised as being at the forefront of child safety '.
In fact, evidence before the Commission shows that the YMCA has been informed that it has received the second lowest assessment of four possible in a quality audit of the Department of Education and Communities (Ministry of Education) in August of the year.
Hare, who started at the YMCA at 21, admitted that the management had failed "from me to the bottom" in the recruitment of Lord and did not ensure that employees were aware of their obligations to report violations of the children's safety guidelines.
At the beginning of the year, Lord was sentenced for sexual offences against twelve boys during his two-year work for the YMCA.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
Hare, however, denied that the YMCA had a cultural problem that prevented employees from reporting Lord's violations of the safety of children.
The staff said they had observed violations, among other things, that Lord was alone with children, cared for them privately as a babysitter, let them sit on his lap, told one that he loved it, and let children play with his phone.
Danielle Ockwell, whose superior Lord, who had asked for a child protection training because she was concerned about his behaviour, said that the child service manager Jacqui Barnat, who was the superior Lord in the YMCA Caringbah, was "very intimidating and very unapproachable for most of the time."
The Managing Director said that he would not accept statements from employees that they would not have dared to report to their superiors.
Instead, he said, their friendship with Lord had affected their judgment, which is why they would not have reported him.
Hare said that he had informed the board of the YMCA NSW that the lesson that the organisation had to draw from the "Jonathan Lord incident" was "not reporting" by employees, and the board had agreed to it.
Hare said that the decision to urge the staff to sign confidentiality obligations shortly after the allegations were made was made by the director of the children's services of the YMCA, Liam Whitley.
He said that this should prevent contamination of the evidence, but this had been "overzealous" and badly implemented.
The YMCA NSW was not a child-safe organisation in the period when Jonathan Lord was employed there between 2009 and 2011, Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University, expert on child sexual abuse, explained to the Commission.
He explained that there had been "serious problems" in the recruitment, review, consultation, training and supervision of staff.
The hearing was postponed until 20 December.
