Scientists were able to shed more light on the context in which a dog's tail-weaving is associated with his mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with their tail waved more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left side.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and react to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "In humans it is well known that the left and right half of the brain react differently to stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions."
Here we have tried to look at this with other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right half of the brain is responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the feelings.
In order to learn more about how dogs react to the side swinging of their species, the researchers monitored the animals while these films looked at other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged legs and analysed the behaviour.
We'll probably soon understand why the tail is moving in one direction, in the other direction
Professor Vallortigara said, "We have shown the dogs films with dogs - either a true version of nature or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we have been able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or to the right."
When the animals saw an otherwise expressive dog move the tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the weaving dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail was mainly left (again from the point of view of the dog who wanders), their heart rate increased and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
He is rather convinced that the dogs had learned from experience, in which movements they should be worried and when not.
He said, "If you have different encounters with other dogs, and if you have a wobble with a tail in one direction rather than a friendly behavior, and the right side rather produces a less friendly behavior, then you react on the basis of these experiences."
The researchers say that the findings of dog owners, veterinarians and trainers could help to better understand the emotions of their animal.
John Bradshaw, an expert in dog behaviour and guest scholarship at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine at the University of Bristol, said that this was not the first study to examine whether the left and the right were important for dogs.
Last year, a team of the University of Lincoln found out that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog and to the right when it's a satisfied dog.
In another research work at the University of Victoria in Canada, the following was said: "Dogs are more likely to go to a robot dog if their" tail "wanders to the left and not to the right instead of getting restless - just the other way around than in the Italian study."
According to his statement, the differences could be due to the fact that in the various studies the dogs did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs respond to real dogs could help, he said.
"Although there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two brain halves are used for different purposes, many of the details still have to be determined - and dogs are no exception," says Bradshaw.
But since their behavior can be simply recorded, it will probably not take long to understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other direction.
