On the way through mud, rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical assistance in remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
In the West African country there are not many doctors, only one for 5,000 people
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 of the "CNN Heroes of 2013."
You can vote for him or one of the other heroes in the top 10 to choose him to be the "CNN Hero of the Year."
The winner will receive $250,000 to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, George Bwelle watched his sick father lose consciousness and went to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
In 1981, Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon.
At first he had only one broken arm, but then there was an inflammation that spread to his brain and caused a hematoma to affect him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," says Georges Bwelle.
We would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years with his father in crowded hospitals and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy," comments Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5: 00 in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and you're not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwell's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon there is only one doctor for 5,000 people, according to the World Health Organisation.
In contrast, the ratio in the United States is for a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for them, most of the comrades could not afford to visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and almost three-quarters of the country's health expenditure are private.
"The only problem they have is poverty," says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
To see his father and so many of his compatriots suffer, in Bwelle made the decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team performed 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which is travelling on weekends in rural areas and offers free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped almost 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people forced himself into small buses and with the cordless medical equipment on the roof, drive over unfixed terrain into the villages that need help.
It's not always going smoothly.
They had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud more than once.
But when they arrive, they will be received like heroes: a feast, a singing and a dance and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a reason to celebrate and bwelle - with its wide smile and its boundless energy - is happy to be present at the happy celebration.
The next morning, the team will start the examination of hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per trip," says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometres around the village - and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others get crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates - a document required for school, but many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anaesthetic.
The operations usually take place in a school, town hall or apartment; after the procedure the patients stand up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next.
The lighting for the surgery and the disinfectant equipment is fed by the group's generator and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of the morning on Sunday.
It's a strenuous pensum, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
"They drum all night so we can stay awake and continue our work," says Bwelle.
On Sunday the team then goes back to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group - a mixture of Cambodian doctors and foreign medical students - carried out 700 free operations last year, and knows that with its work it creates a huge difference for the people it helps.
One man said that the free operation of a colon that he had received now enabled him to work again.
"This changes the future of my family," said the man.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job he financed 60% of his non-profit activities, said Bwelle; the rest came from private donations.
"I really don't know when he's sleeping," says Katie O'Malley, who studies medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia in the second year and works voluntarily in Bwelle's group.
He's always in the hospital, or he's trying to make money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students such as O'Malley, who come from the US and Europe and support Bwelle, this is an opportunity to gain practical experience that they would never get at home.
"We can be in operations where we help to dab blood or hold the instruments for Dr. Bwelle," explains O'Malley.
This would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
The students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and bring with them often donated medical material.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, the transport and the instruction.
"He is without a doubt a hero," says O'Malley.
He devotes his life to this organization and his desire to help the people of Cameroon knows no limits.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life and thus fulfilling a promise that he has given to his father gives him great joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this work," says Bwelle.
And I'm thinking of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
