Tourism: descent to the Romans
A drainage channel from the Roman era is preserved below Cologne on a length of about 120 metres.
If you visit Cologne, you will not pass the cathedral.
The two towers rise to the sky and make it the second-highest church building in Europe.
But few visitors who admire the two filigree church towers are aware that there is a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in the field of Cologne's underworld.
The meeting point for its guided tours is the service center of Cologne-Tourisme directly at the Dom.
The tour starts unspectacular: "We start in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the seventies the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and so the remains of the old city walls only stopped what was not too big.
Most of the users of the car park now also run past the Roman remains and only turn off their car.
But those who look more closely, discover in the park deck D2 an archaeological site separated by metal bars.
There are about five meters high ruins of hand-made stones.
"The remains of the Roman city wall, built in the second half of the first century after Christ," says Schulze.
Before it goes back to the light of day, Schulze lets the participants on the upper park level take a look into a dark, 15-metre deep shaft.
This is the well of the old cathedral, which is unfortunately hardly perceived.
The next station of the tour is the Preitorium, and here the participants get back down into the depth.
Here we experience the seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the pretor of the CCAA.
What CAA means is a visitor.
"The abbreviation stands for" Colonia Claudia Ara Agripinensium, "which means in good German as" City of Roman Law and City of Agripineser, founded under Emperor Claudius at the place of the altar for the emperor cult. "
And the preitorium is the former governor's palace, the center of power of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the front of the exhibition, a tunnel access leads to the Roman sewer canal, which is preserved here on about 120 meters long.
"You can walk along the so-called Cloaca Maxima, if you want," Schulze encourages the guests.
There's a surprise for Schulze.
After he has taken the key at the checkout, he leads the group to a 16-metre-deep, walk-in shaft.
"We are now in the Mikwe, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built its bath deep into the ground to get to the groundwater that was essential for the ritual washing.
In the lower end of the Mikwe, whose origins go back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read by changing levels of the Rhine.
The Mikwe is part of an archaeological zone in the town hall square, for which the construction work is to begin shortly.
However, a few years will pass before the completion.
