John Kerry, in an unprecedented admission, states that the US espionage has "gone too far inappropriately"
John Kerry, with an unexpected admission, indicated a softening of the US's defensive attitude towards its monitoring programmes by saying that in certain cases the espionage had "gone unreasonably far."
The Foreign Minister also admitted that he, together with Barack Obama, was responsible for the fact that they had been switched to "autopilot" when the explosive revelations of the Whistleblower Edward Snowden became public about the NSA's espionage activities.
The leaked information has led the US government to a diplomatic storm of indignation on the part of its allies.
In a video-broadcast speech at the Open Government Conference in London, Kerry said: "The President and I, as well as others in the government, have learned of some things that have actually been done by autopilot, simply because the ability to do so was still due to the Second World War and the difficult years of the Cold War and, of course, to the 11 September."
He was the first high-level member of the US government to admit that the US espionage had crossed a border, but also stressed that no rights had been abused.
He said, "In some cases, this has gone too far."
The President is determined to make it clear and is therefore carrying out a thorough investigation so that no one has to feel that there is abuse.
I assure you that the rights of innocent persons in this process will not be affected.
However, Kerry insisted that the NSA was a force of good and that many lives had been saved through its monitoring.
He added: "We are dealing with a new world in which people are ready to blow themselves up."
There is a radical extremism in the world that is committed to killing people, blowing up and attacking governments.
So what if you were able to intercept and stop this before it happened?
We have actually prevented aircraft falls, attacks on buildings and the murder of people, because we have experienced in advance of such plans.
Meanwhile, US legislators will travel to Europe to dispel the concerns about the alleged American espionage and convince Europeans of the need to continue to work with the US in the anti-terror efforts, as the Chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on European Affairs said on Thursday.
Senator Chris Murphy from Connecticut said that he had spoken to representatives of the European Parliament and other people this week and was concerned about their threats of no longer participating in anti-terror organisations because of the frustration of the National Security Agency's surveillance.
"It is very important for the US's national security interests that Europeans remain on board with a view to our joint efforts against terrorism," said Murphy, who is a Democrat for the first time in the Senate and is the Chairman of the Senate Subcommittee on Foreign Relations and European Affairs, in an interview in Washington.
I am also going to Europe to make it clear that we must continue to work together in the fight against terrorism, regardless of their annoyance about the NSA programmes.
The media reports that the NSA has collected millions of phone data in Europe have burdened relations with some US allies, although the head of the intelligence service this week said that the reports were incorrect and based on a misunderstanding of the metadata collected by NATO allies and exchanged with the United States.
Other revelations quoted from documents passed by Snowden, according to which the NSA had monitored the phone of Chancellor Angela Merkel and up to 34 other heads of state worldwide.
The head of the national intelligence services, James Clapper, defended the espionage of allies as necessary and declared that this was common on both sides.
In all this turmoil, Murphy said that his authority was preparing the mission of the Congress to take place this year, and hoped that the delegation would include members from both parties and chambers.
The names of the other participating Members will be published in the coming days.
He said the exact route was still being worked out.
While Murphy stressed that the purpose of the journey was to improve relations, he also said that there would be some "serious words."
He said that European governments must be honest with their people about the type of spy programmes they have been using for years.
"While we can change our monitoring programmes to better protect the rights of Europeans, they must also agree with the fact that we are not the only ones who spy," Murphy said.
In the meantime, John Kerry is on a weekend trip to the Middle East and Poland to deal with the resentment of the US strategy in Syria, Egypt and Iran, as well as the US surveillance activities.
